/*

	Connected Cellular Nodes
	------------------------

	Using rounded Voronoi diffusion masks to create a pattern with a bio organic flavor 
	resembling connected cellular nodes... or to put it another way, it's a variation on 
	Aeikick's "Trabeculum Reaction Diffusion" example. :) The pattern is legible in 
	under ten seconds and reaches a relative state of equilibrium in under 60 seconds.

	The basic idea behind Aiekick's example was to produce masks to control the way in which
	reactancts A and B interact with the system. Visually speaking, it's a way of 
	influencing the dark and bright sections of the resultant reaction diffusion pattern.

	For the masks, instead of Fabrice's tri-nodal distance formula (which happens to resemble 
	bone trabeculae, hence the name, trabeculum), I've used some rounded Voronoi that is 
	based on Tomkh's rounded Voronoi border refinements. I've also applied separate masks
	to the feed and kill variables.

	Cellular lines were used for the kill mask to force some cellular borders and a similar 
	feed mask created a clear section just inside the cells. The rest was just a regular 
	Gray-Scott diffusion pattern. Combined with a little color and shading, the result is a 
	kind of randomly connected amoeba party. :)

	I finally got in amongst it and coded a fixed sized texture. I occasionally play around 
	with 3D arrays packed into 2D textures, so it was just a case of repurposing code from  
    that. It mightn't seem like much, but having a procedurally generated texture that 
	behaves in the same way as a regular in-house Shadertoy texture makes life so much 
	easier. For one, switching canvas size results in the same pattern creation. Plus
	repeat textures can be applied to surfaces without any hassle. Also, aspect correct
	coordinates produce an apect correct texture.

	By the way, I've produced a 3D reaction diffusion example that I'll release shortly.


	Inspired by:

	// I get a lot of inspiration from the French coders on here. :)
	Trabeculum Reaction Diffusion - aiekick
	https://www.shadertoy.com/view/MsKfDR

*/

// Texture maping function. This one is arranged to wrap according to the specified
// texture size, which can be set in the "Common" code tab. It differs ever so slightly
// to the same function in "BufA" tab in that it's scaled by the texture size as well.
vec4 texMap(sampler2D tx, vec2 p) { 

    // The newer "texelFetch" function. I had it in my head that the old way would be 
    // more compatible, compile faster, and "might" render faster inside a raymarching
    // equation, but I honestly wouldn't know. If anyone does, feel free to let me know. :)
    //return texelFetch(tx, ivec2(mod(p*dSize, dSize)), 0);

    // Returning the correct pixel... using the usual unwieldly mess. :) Normally, I'd 
    // have to use "floor(p*dSize)," but things seem to working without it.
    return texture(tx, (mod(p*dSize, dSize) + .5)/iChannelResolution[0].xy); 
}

void mainImage( out vec4 fragColor, in vec2 fragCoord )
{
    // Aspect correct screen coordinates.
    vec2 uv = (fragCoord - iResolution.xy*.5)/iResolution.y;

    // Normalized screen coordinates, used for vignettes, 
    // color gradient overlays, etc.
    vec2 uv0 = fragCoord/iResolution.xy;

    // Scrolling.
    uv -= vec2(1, .5)*iTime/8.;

    // Rotation, to give the pattern a slightly more random look.
    mat2 rot = r2(3.14159/6.);
    uv *= rot;

    // Hassle free changes in texture size. :)
    //uv /= 1.5;

    // Three diffusion texture samples. The regular one, and one offset slightly
    // to creat the drop shadow, and a higher frequency sample for a light
    // background pattern.
    vec4 tx = texMap(iChannel0, uv);
    vec4 tx2 = texMap(iChannel0, uv - vec2(3., -2)*rot/iResolution.y);
    vec4 tx3 = texMap(iChannel0, uv*3.);

    // Create a very simple color gradient background with an overlay.
    vec3 bg = mix(vec3(1, .6, .3), vec3(1, .8, .2), uv0.y); // Vertical color gradient.
    bg = mix(bg, vec3(0), (1. - smoothstep(0., .1, tx3.x - .5))*.2); // Fine pattern overlay.
    bg = mix(bg, bg.yxz, uv0.x - .25); // Horizontal color gradient mixing.
    bg *= tx2.x*1.1; // Applying the drop shadow to the background.

    // Initiate the scene color to the background.
    vec3 col = bg.zyx;


    // Apply the main diffusion pattern.
    col = mix(col, vec3(0), 1. - smoothstep(0., .1, tx.x - .45));


    // Coloring in the cells. It's a very basic white with a drop shadow, overlayed with 
    // black black, which is almost redundant, but if you wanted different colors,
    // etc, this would be neccessary.
    vec3 cellCol = mix(vec3(1)*tx2.x, vec3(0), 1. - smoothstep(0., .1, tx.x - .5));

    // The mask used in the diffusion process is stored in the "Z" channel.
    // It's just some rounded Voronoi, but it saves a extra function call, 
    // plus changes only need to be applied in the "Buf A" tab.
    //vec2 v = Voronoi(uv, vec2(6));
    float mask = tx.z;
    // Applying the cell contents to the scene.
    col = mix(col, cellCol, (1. - smoothstep(0., .1, -mask + .1))*(1. - tx.y));


    // Square vignette -- I was too lazy to write my own square vignette code, so I 
    // "borrowed" and adapted a segment from Flockaroo's amazing "when voxels wed pixels"
    // example, which you can find here: https://www.shadertoy.com/view/MsKfRw
    //
    // On a side note, I'm going to put together an example that applies his cross
    // hatching formula. I just need to find the right scene to do it justice. 
    vec2 scc=(fragCoord-.5*iResolution.xy)/iResolution.x;
    float vign = 1.1 - .3*dot(scc, scc);
    vign*= 1. - .75*exp(-sin(uv0.x*3.14159)*20.*iResolution.x/iResolution.y);
    vign*= 1. - .75*exp(-sin(uv0.y*3.14159)*20.);
    col *= vign;

    // Rough gamma correction.
    fragColor = vec4(sqrt(max(col, 0.)), 1);

}

// The texture size. Because there are no fixed size buffers, we have to be careful with 
// size. Obviously, if using a canvas with smaller dimensions, this would break, but who'd
// be viewing things in a window that small. :) Jokes aside, if someone could give me a
// compelling reason, I could put some resize code in for times when the resolution falls
// below this threshold.
//
// By the way, I was using these weird dimensions to test that the wrapping and mapping 
// routines work. Plus, I was using something that wrapped by a factor of six, so the
// following numbers tie in with that.
const vec2 dSize = vec2(240, 180);

// Standard 2D rotation formula.
mat2 r2(in float a){ float c = cos(a), s = sin(a); return mat2(c, -s, s, c); }

// vec2 to float.
float hash21(vec2 p, vec2 dim) { 

    p = mod(p, dim);
    return fract(sin(dot(p, vec2(1.27, 113.93)))*43758.5453);
}

// 2x2 hash algorithm.
vec2 hash22(vec2 p, vec2 dim) { 

    p = mod(p, dim);
    // More concise, but wouldn't disperse things as nicely as the block below.
    float n = sin(dot(p,vec2(113, 1))); 
    return fract(vec2(2097152, 262144)*n);

    // Animation.
    //p = fract(vec2(2097152, 262144)*n);
    //return sin(p*6.2831853 + iTime)*0.5 + 0.5;
}

// 2x2 hash algorithm.
vec2 hash22B(vec2 p, vec2 dim) { 

    p = mod(p, dim);
    // More concise, but wouldn't disperse things as nicely as the block below.
    float n = sin(dot(p,vec2(113, 1))); 
    return fract(vec2(2097152, 262144)*n)*.7;

    // Animation.
    //p = fract(vec2(2097152, 262144)*n);
    //return sin(p*6.2831853 + iTime)*0.35 + 0.35;
}

// IQ's exponential-based smooth minimum function. Unlike the polynomial-based
// smooth minimum, this one is associative and commutative.
float sminExp(float a, float b, float k){

    float res = exp(-k*a) + exp(-k*b);
    return -log(res)/k;
}

// With variable distance smoothing, it's probably not technically correct, but
// you can't tell the difference. :)
#define FAST_EXP

// Exponential smoothing.
float sExp(float a, float k){

    return exp(-k*a);
}

// Commutative smooth minimum function. Provided by Tomkh and taken from 
// Alex Evans's (aka Statix) talk: 
// http://media.lolrus.mediamolecule.com/AlexEvans_SIGGRAPH-2015.pdf
// Credited to Dave Smith @media molecule.
float smin(float a, float b, float r){

   float f = max(0., 1. - abs(b - a)/r);
   return min(a, b) - r*.25*f*f;
}

vec2 cellID; // Individual Voronoi cell IDs.


// 2D 2nd-order Voronoi: Obviously, this is just a rehash of IQ's original. I've tidied
// The is a variation on a regular 2-pass Voronoi traversal that produces a Voronoi
// pattern based on the interior cell point to the nearest cell edge (as opposed
// to the nearest offset point). It's a slight reworking of Tomkh's example, which
// in turn, is based on IQ's original example. The links are below:
//
// On a side note, I have no idea whether a faster solution is possible, but when I
// have time, I'm going to try to find one anyway.
//
// Voronoi distances - iq
// https://www.shadertoy.com/view/ldl3W8
//
// Here's IQ's well written article that describes the process in more detail.
// https://iquilezles.org/articles/voronoilines
//
// Faster Voronoi Edge Distance - tomkh
// https://www.shadertoy.com/view/llG3zy
vec2 Voronoi(in vec2 p, in vec2 dim){

    p *= dim;

    // One of Tomkh's snippets that includes a wrap to deal with
    // larger numbers, which is pretty cool.

#if 1
    // Slower, but handles big numbers better.
    vec2 n = floor(p);
    p -= n;
    vec2 h = step(.5, p) - 1.5;
    n += h; p -= h;
#else
    vec2 n = floor(p - 1.);
    p -= n;
#endif

    // Storage for all sixteen hash values. The same set of hash values are
    // reused in the second pass, and since they're reasonably expensive to
    // calculate, I figured I'd save them from resuse. However, I could be
    // violating some kind of GPU architecture rule, so I might be making 
    // things worse... If anyone knows for sure, feel free to let me know.
    //
    // I've been informed that saving to an array of vectors is worse.
    //vec2 svO[3];

    // Individual Voronoi cell ID. Used for coloring, materials, etc.
    cellID = vec2(0); // Redundant initialization, but I've done it anyway.

    // As IQ has commented, this is a regular Voronoi pass, so it should be
    // pretty self explanatory.
    //
    // First pass: Regular Voronoi.
	vec2 mo, o;

    // Minimum distance, "smooth" distance to the nearest cell edge, regular
    // distance to the nearest cell edge, and a line distance place holder.
    float md = 8., lMd = 8., lMd2 = 8., lnDist, d;

    for( int j=0; j<3; j++ )
    for( int i=0; i<3; i++ ){

        o = vec2(i, j);
        o += hash22B(n + o, dim) - p;
        // Saving the hash values for reuse in the next pass. I don't know for sure,
        // but I've been informed that it's faster to recalculate the had values in
        // the following pass.
        //svO[j*3 + i] = o; 

        // Regular squared cell point to nearest node point.
        d = dot(o, o); 

        if( d<md ){

            md = d;  // Update the minimum distance.
            // Keep note of the position of the nearest cell point - with respect
            // to "p," of course. It will be used in the second pass.
            mo = o; 
            cellID = vec2(i, j) + n; // Record the cell ID also.
        }

    }

    #ifdef FAST_EXP
    lMd = 0.;
    #endif

    // Second pass: Distance to closest border edge. The closest edge will be one of the edges of
    // the cell containing the closest cell point, so you need to check all surrounding edges of 
    // that cell, hence the second pass... It'd be nice if there were a faster way.
    for( int j=0; j<3; j++ )
    for( int i=0; i<3; i++ ){

        // I've been informed that it's faster to recalculate the hash values, rather than 
        // access an array of saved values.
        o = vec2(i, j);
        o += hash22B(n + o, dim) - p;
        // I went through the trouble to save all sixteen expensive hash values in the first 
        // pass in the hope that it'd speed thing up, but due to the evolving nature of 
        // modern architecture that likes everything to be declared locally, I might be making 
        // things worse. Who knows? I miss the times when lookup tables were a good thing. :)
        // 
        //o = svO[j*3 + i];

        // Skip the same cell... I found that out the hard way. :D
        if( dot(o-mo, o-mo)>.00001 ){ 

            // This tiny line is the crux of the whole example, believe it or not. Basically, it's
            // a bit of simple trigonometry to determine the distance from the cell point to the
            // cell border line. See IQ's article for a visual representation.
            lnDist = dot( 0.5*(o+mo), normalize(o-mo));

            // Abje's addition. Border distance using a smooth minimum. Insightful, and simple.
            //
            // On a side note, IQ reminded me that the order in which the polynomial-based smooth
            // minimum is applied effects the result. However, the exponentional-based smooth
            // minimum is associative and commutative, so is more correct. In this particular case, 
            // the effects appear to be negligible, so I'm sticking with the cheaper polynomial-based 
            // smooth minimum, but it's something you should keep in mind. By the way, feel free to 
            // uncomment the exponential one and try it out to see if you notice a difference.
            //
            // // Polynomial-based smooth minimum.
            //lMd = smin(lMd, lnDist, lnDist*.5); 
            //
            // Exponential-based smooth minimum. By the way, this is here to provide a visual reference 
            // only, and is definitely not the most efficient way to apply it. To see the minor
            // adjustments necessary, refer to Tomkh's example here: Rounded Voronoi Edges Analysis - 
            // https://www.shadertoy.com/view/MdSfzD

            #ifdef FAST_EXP
            lMd += sExp(lnDist, (lnDist)*30.);
            #else
            lMd = sminExp(lMd, lnDist, (lnDist)*30.); 
            #endif

            // Minimum regular straight-edged border distance. If you only used this distance,
            // the web lattice would have sharp edges.
            lMd2 = min(lMd2, lnDist);
        }

    }

    #ifdef FAST_EXP
    lMd = -log(lMd)/((lMd)*30.);
    #endif

    // Return the smoothed and unsmoothed distance. I think they need capping at zero... but 
    // I'm not positive.
    return max(vec2(lMd, lMd2), 0.);
}

